    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1899-02-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1899-02-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="6"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d6">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Buchanan</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1899-02-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 16, 1899</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 454.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I inclose copy of a letter from Messrs. Briesen
                    &amp; Knauth, of New York City, complaining that the trade-marks and symbols of
                    United States citizens are improperly appropriated in the Argentine
                    Republic.</p>
                <p>You will give the subject attention in the way of inquiry and, if convenient
                    occasion offers, of suggestion to the minister for foreign affairs in the
                    direction of an understanding which would remove or lessen the ground of
                    complaint.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Inclosure.]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <persName type="from">Briesen &amp; Knauth</persName> to Mr. <persName
                                type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1899-02-08">
                                <hi rend="italic">February 8, 1899</hi>
                            </date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Clients of ours, large exporters of ware made
                        in the United States to South American countries, especially to Brazil and
                        the Argentine Republic, complain to us that citizens of these countries are
                        permitted to bodily appropriate and register as their own the trade-marks
                        and symbols of United States citizens and to thus shut out importations from
                        this country or else force the importer to buy back from them the right
                        which is justly his own.</p>
                    <p>We write to ask if any confirmation or denial of this alleged state of facts
                        is obtainable through your Department, and to request that the United States
                        diplomatic or consular officers in these countries be communicated with on
                        this subject, with the view to determining whether the practice complained
                        of exists, and whether, if it does, there is any adequate remedy.</p>
                    <p>The favor of an answer is respectfully requested.</p>
                    <p>Very respectfully,</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Briesen &amp; Knauth.</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
